The obligation of residence could not be easily enforced‚ especially by a Bishop who had ignored it for most of his adult life. A constitution of Pope Boniface V111.² had sanctioned dispensations in the case of the many minors—-kinsmen often of the patrous—instituted to parochial cume, for whom clerical training, and even higher education with recourse to necessary books could hardly be provided except at a centre oi general study. All the Bishops therefore granted licences to young Rectors and Archdeacons to go to Paris or to Oxford to pursue their studies, or have a pleasant time, if they were idle ; and sometimes a tax was levied from them for the benefit of the fabric fund of the Cathedral. The licences were limited commonly at first to one or two years, but occasionally they spread over as many as seven. There was little security meantime that the purposes for which these were granted were fulfilled; the young incumbente failed frequently to appear for ordination at the stated times, and we. hear therefore often of sequestrations for default.⁸ Men of* influence again and high-born ladies expected their nominees to attend them as their private chaplainS‚ and their desires could not be always disregarded. The Crown had no scruple in using its ecclesiastical patronage for the payment of its servants, and angrily warned off the Bishop who was rash enough to summon the non-residents to their cures.⁴ There were many others who gave trouble; aliens intruded by pro- vision of a Pope, or by a Bishop like Peter de Aquablanca. It was difficult to learn if they had any special dispensation 3 they were often far away, and repeated citations were required to ascertain the facts; and hence the somewhat wearisome recurrence of such entries in the Register, and the scanty results of ineffectual attempts at discipline.
